Final Report: Will you survive the Titanic?

Ajinkya Dhage and Shardul Vinchurkar (Group 9)

1. Introduction and Problem Statement

RMS Titanic, a British passenger liner started its journey to the New York City on 10th of April 1912. It collided with a large iceberg on 15th of April 1912 that resulted in the sinking of the largest passenger liner ever made. This tragic accident resulted in deaths of around 1500 people from the reported 2224 passengers on board.

There were many reasons that this incident led to such loss of life, but, amongst all the reasons the main reason was that the number of lifeboats on the ship was not enough to hold all the passengers and crew members. There were certain decisions made while the ship was sinking which was another main reason for this mishap. These decisions were based on the demographics of the passengers, and a certain group of people had a higher chance of survival. Some of the factors that concluded in the survival of certain passengers were Gender, Age and Class/status.

In this project, we propose to develop a model to predict the chance of survival of any given passenger on the Titanic voyage.

2. Data sources and data preparation

The data used for analysis of the passengers survived was taken from Kaggle. (https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data)

2.1 Data attributes

This training data source has 891 instances, the test data has 418 instances and following 12 attributes/columns.

3.2 Data Transformation

Our dataset includes 12 attributes among which Pclass is a numerical attribute which needs to be mapped as a nominal value, given that 1 represents the Upper class, 2 for the middle class and 3 for the lower class.

Also, the Survived attribute in the dataset needs to be mapped as a class value of Yes and No.

#Data Extraction and transformation
#COnverting Pclass to nomainal
titanicTrain$Pclass <- factor(titanicTrain$Pclass, levels = c(1, 2, 3), labels = c("Upper", "Middle", "Lower"))
titanicTest$Pclass <- factor(titanicTest$Pclass, levels = c(1, 2, 3), labels = c("Upper", "Middle", "Lower"))
#Converting Survived to nomainal
titanicTrain$Survived <- factor(titanicTrain$Survived, levels = c(1, 0), labels = c("Yes", "No"))
#Adding Survived to Test
titanicTest$Survived <- NA

When we plot the graph for the survival of passengers we can see the probability of the survival of passengers is around 39%. So we, have an understanding that the possibility of survival of a passenger on the Titanic is quite infrequent. Based on this we tried to visualize the effects of different attributes on the chance of survival.

The plot of gender versus the survival clearly indicates that the chance of survival for women passengers is much higher than that of the male passengers. This helps us realize that the attribute gender is of utmost importance, and needs to be included in our analysis for predicting the chance of survival of any given passneger.

Next, we wanted to see how the social status of the passenger would have affected the survival rate of onboard population. On plotting the graph we can clearly see that the chance of survival is higher for upper-class passengers, as compared to the middle class and lower class. Also, the chance of survival for the lower class is far less than that of any other class.

Then we wanted to confirm how the survival rate is affected by the age of the passengers. So plotting the graph we realize that children and passengers within 9 - 40 age range had a fair chance of survival as compared to old people or people above the age of 55. Thus, helping us understand the importance of the attribute age in our analysis.

There are 2 attributes namely the SibSp and the Parch which stands for sibling spouse and parent children, they necessarily determine how many family members are onboard with the passenger. On plotting the graph for SibSp and Parch versus survival, we observed that a medium sized family had a fairer chance of survival as compared to a single person or a passenger traveling with a large family.

There are other 2 attributes fare and port of embarkation, visualizing fare is difficult because the data is continuous and contains outliers for eg. A passenger has paid $512 for his ticket. Similarly, the port of Embarkation represents where the passenger boarded the Titanic, and seem to have a similar effect on the chance of survival.

3.4 Data Transformation

So when we summarized our data in initial exploration, we realized that there were a lot of missing values in the dataset. Among these missing values, the Embarked attribute had 2 blank values which were not considered as NA but a whole other type, to overcome this problem we replaced the blank values with NA values and treated them as missing data. Then, we combined the train data and the test data to achieve the consistency throughout the dataset (train and test) while filling the missing values. After which, we combined the attributes SibSp and Parch in one attribute named “Family’ based on our initial observation of visualizing the plot of SibSp Vs Survived and Parch Vs Survived.

#Adding NA to Missing Embarked Data
titanicTrain$Embarked[titanicTrain$Embarked == ""] <- NA
#Combining train and test data
titanicData <- rbind(titanicTrain, titanicTest)
#Data Transformation
titanicData$Family <- titanicData$SibSp + titanicData$Parch

3.5 Data Cleansing

After the initial exploration and the visualization of the data, we observed that the attribute Ticket has alphanumeric values and does not provide any demographic information about the passenger. Similarly, the attribute Cabin is irrelevant as it contains a lot of blank values and does not represent any information about the passenger. Also since we have combined the columns SibSp and Parch in Family they are no longer useful on our analysis. In the end, the attribute Name also does not contribute much towards the final prediction. Hence, we drop all these columns from our dataset.

#Data Cleaning
drops <- c("Name", "SibSp", "Parch", "Ticket", "Cabin")

4. Methodology

As discussed we have a lot of missing instances in our dataset. The methodology we will be following here would be as follows:

  • Using different cleansing methods to fill in the missing values
    • Mean: In this method, we will calculate the mean of the attribute and assign it to all the missing values in that attribute.
    • KNN: The KNN algorithm in R predicts the missing values by grouping the data instance based on Euclidean distance.
    • Linear regression: We will build a predictive model using regression to predict the missing values in our data.
  • For each cleansing method we will build different models
    • Naive Bayes
    • Decision Tree
    • SVM
    • Random Forest
    • General Linear Model

#Evaluation of model
TN <- confusion["No", "No"]
FN <- confusion["No", "Yes"]
TP <- confusion["Yes", "Yes"]
FP <- confusion["Yes", "No"]
nbAccuracy <- (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN) #Accuracy
nbPrecision <- TP / (TP + FP) #Precision
nbRecall <- TP / (TP + FN) #Recall
nbF <- nbPrecision * nbRecall * 2/(nbPrecision + nbRecall) #F-Measure
#Computing the Chance Agreement
p1e <- (TN + FN)/(TP + TN + FP + FN) * (TN + FP)/(TP + TN + FP + FN)
p2e <- (TP + FP)/(TP + TN + FP + FN) * (TP + FN)/(TP + TN + FP + FN)
pe <- p1e + p2e
nbKappa <- (nbAccuracy - pe)/(1 - pe) #Kappa

6. Results and Evaluation

We have used three different methods to predict the missing values of age in our data. And build a classification model for each of these data cleansing methods.

First, we filled the missing values in Age and Fare by considering the mean of the attribute over the entire data and replaced the blank values in the Embarked attribute with the mode of that attribute. Then, using the cleaned training data we first build a Naive Bayes model which resulted in 83% in accuracy and 62% in Kappa, which is a fairly good model. Then, we used the same train and test data and build predictive models using Decision trees, SVM, Random Forest and general linear models. which provided Accuracy, precision, Recall, F-Measure and Kappa as shown in the above table. SVM proved to be the best model for this data cleansing method with 85% accuracy and 68% Kappa.

Then, in our second method, we built a predictive model for predicting the missing values of age, fare and embarked in our dataset with a hope that our model would make a better-educated guess. KNN algorithm generates groups of data based on the attributes and measuring the similarity by Euclidean distance. In this method, we also tried to categorize the instances of the attribute family into 3 classes, namely, Single, middle and large family. Again, separating the training data provided from this cleaner data, we build our train and test sets to build our models. Similar to the first method we built predictive models using Naive Bayes, Decision Trees, SVM, Random Forest and General Linear Models. In this method, GLM proved to be a better model with 84% accuracy and 66% Kappa value.

In our last method, we built a predictive model using regression to predict our missing age values. And similar to last two methods, we built predictive models using Naive Bayes, Decision Trees, SVM, Random Forest and General Linear Models. In this case, Random Forest turned out to be a winner with 84% accuracy and 66% Kappa. And, as we can see that in all of the models, Method 1 SVM performed the best with 85% accuracy and 68% Kappa.

As this result is based on the provided training data, we evaluated our best model on the given test data which yielded a result of 78.47% as shown in the image below. Currently, Kaggle is using just the 50% of the test data to evaluate the score of the model, the final results may improve if the remaining test data is used.

dropsForSvm <- c("Survived")
svmTest <- method1DataTest[, !names(method1DataTest) %in% dropsForSvm]

SVMPredResult <- ifelse(predict(method1SVM, svmTest, type = "class") == "Yes", 1, 0)

SVMResult <- titanicTest
SVMResult$Survived <- SVMPredResult
write.csv(SVMResult, file = "SVMResult.csv", row.names = F)

7. Major Challenges

Data Cleansing:

In analyzing the data and building a predictive model to predict the outcome of any new instance whether or not that particular instance would survive, we realized that cleansing of the data properly is extremely important, not only because we could lose information but also some models cannot handle missing values in the data.

We felt cleaning the data as the most challenging task in our project, as we were unable to find the best way to tackle 263 missing age values from 1309 instances, which is 20% of the available data, and this number is huge when it comes to building predictive models.

We as humans prefer categorical data as it delivers more insight, but the algorithms prefer to work with numerical data. This often leads to unexpected results, as some of the instances draw the prediction towards them just due to their mass. This leads to a confusion, of which attributes should be kept categorical and which should be kept numerical.

Availability of data:

The Second challenge we faced is the availability of the data. Though our models almost reached 85% accuracy, we could have generated better model if the available data for training was more than 891 instances. In addition to this, the available data has 20% missing values for the attribute Age, which is one of the dominant attributes that contribute to the prediction of the passenger survival.

8. Conclusion

Based on our analysis we can interpret that the attributes such as the Gender, Age, Social status, number of family members onboard and the port of embarkation of a passenger provide us useful information about the demographics of the passenger and assists us in building an efficient model that would predict the chance of the passenger’s survival on the Titanic. However, the other attributes such as Ticket Number, cabinet and the name of the passenger are comparatively less dominant and provide no useful information towards the prediction of the survival rate.

While building the models we realized that the available data is not of prime quality, because of the inconsistencies in the available data such as 263 missing values of the attribute Age which is one of the important attributes. Also, the available instances for training the data was not sufficient enough to get the model to predict with an accuracy of more than 85%. In order to deal with this missing values in the attribute Age, we used three different methodologies to load the missing values that are the mean method, KNN, linear regression models. In the mean method, we replaced the missing values with the mean of the attributes that contain the missing values. KNN model was used as another method which predicted and replaced the missing values. At last, we built a regression model to predict the missing age values. For each of this method, we built Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, SVM, Random Forest and General Linear Models. On the evaluation of each model, we concluded that SVM proved to be a better model when the data cleansing was performed by the mean method. It was successful in achieving an accuracy of 85% and a kappa value of 68%. This can be improved by using feature selection methods, Feature engineering methods, which was not implemented in this project due to the limited amount of time.

Though we used predictive models to load missing values and assisting our models in taking a better-educated guess, the models did not differ much from the models that were built using the mean method. We believe that building a model to predict the missing age values based on Gender, social status and number of family members on board would never result in accurate determinations. Thus, assisting our argument of the need for more data.

We used 2 basic classification models and 3 advanced classification models in our analysis methods. Though we know that these models are efficient in the world of data analytics and machine learning, we believe that each model performs better for a particular type of data. In our case SVM proved to be the best model for predicting the survival of the passengers on Titanic is because our data was sparse in nature, easy to visualize and having a distinct boundary to separate the two classes of Yes and No. GLM and Random forest perform well when there are multi-dimensions in the data or visualizing the data are difficult, whereas the data we have is binary and limited. Naive Bayes is based on probability and would perform better in comparison to SVM when the data does not have a clear/distinct boundary, so will the Decision tree.

In conclusion, we would like to say, that working on this project had a great learning curve, we realized the importance of cleaning of the data, visualizing the attributes to understand the meaning and the relations behind them, the purpose of transforming the data provided to models to assist them in making better predictions.
